std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
  // NOTE: This function provides a simplified conversion. 
  // It handles basic Markdown elements and doesn't consider all possible variations.
  std::string html;
  std::istringstream ss(markdown);
  std::string word;

  std::uint32_t escapeIndex = 0; // keep track of escaping index in the html string
  while (std::getline(ss, word, ' ')) {
    if (word == "**") {
      html += "<strong>";  // Bold text
    } else if (word == "***") {
      html += "<em>";   // *emphasis
    } else if (word == "*") {
      html += "<em>"; // *italic
    } else if (word == "#" ) { // headings
      html += "<p>";
      html += "<h1";
      html += escapeToHTML(word, word.length());
      html += ">";
    } else if (word == "\"") {
      html += "<a href=\"";
      html += escapeToHTML(word, word.length());
      html += "\"";
    } else if (word == "```") { // highlighting code
      html += "<pre>";
    } else if (word == "```" || html.empty()) { // close </p> and other elements
      html += "</p>"; 
    } 
    else { 
      html += word;
    } 
  }
  // ... (Handle remaining Markdown elements like links, images, lists, quotes, etc.)


  return html;
}

std::string escapeToHTML(const std::string& text, std::size_t len) {
  std::stringstream ss("");
  for (std::size_t i = 0; i < len; ++i) {
      char c = text[i];
      switch (c) {
        case '<':
          ss << "&lt;";
          break; // Less than sign
        case '>':
          ss << "&gt;";
          break; // Greater than sign
        case '&':
          ss << "&amp;";
          break;  // Ampersand
        default:
          ss << c; 
          break;
      }
  }
  return ss.str(); // return the escaped html string
}

```

**Explanation**

1. **`markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown)`:**
   - Takes a `std::string` containing markdown text as input.
   - Creates an empty `std::string` called `html` to store the resulting HTML.
   - It uses `std::istringstream` to iterate through the markdown text.

2. **Iterate over Markdown:**
   - The function breaks the input markdown into individual words using `std::getline` and a `' '` as a delimiter. 
   - Checks if the word is a Markdown instruction (bold, italics, headings, etc.). 
   - If it is, the corresponding HTML tags are constructed.
   -  The escaping logic ensures valid HTML by replacing special characters with their HTML equivalents or simply copying the raw character. 

3. **`escapeToHTML(const std::string& text, std::size_t len)`:**
   - This helper function allows for any special character. 
   - A simple string stream is used to iterate through the characters in the text and convert them to their proper HTML escaped versions when necessary

**Note:** This simplified code does not handle all possible Markdown elements.


**Example Usage**

